There are lots of ways around this, but in my opinion, you should not be coding this the way you have it.

You can use an AtomicReference to create a Reference to a String.

    AtomicReference&lt;String&gt; statusMessage = new AtomicReference&lt;&gt;();
    AtomicReference&lt;String&gt; error = new AtomicReference&lt;&gt;();

....

    statusMessage.set(&quot;Disconnected&quot;);
    error.set(e.getMessage());
....

    return new Object() {
       public String connection = statusMessage.get();
       public String message = error.get();
    };


This will solve your issue, but returning a raw Object is going to cause many more headaches for you.  Create a POJO, even if it&#39;s a simple DTO, for your responses.  This will enable you to provide better API documentation, as well as write effective unit tests, as well as provide type-checking.

